e 1474","1441":"1441","1474":"1474","1507":"1507","3 July 1474":"3 July 1474","England":"England","West Woodhay, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"West Woodhay, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Faringdon, Berkshire, England":"Faringdon, Berkshire, England","Woodhay, Berkshire, England":"Woodley, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Shottesbroke was born before 1399, in Woodley, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Gilbert Shottisbroke, was 49 and his mother, Elizabeth Standon, was 38. He had at least 1 daughter with Edith Stourton. He died before 1474."},"et":{"Bef 1399–Bef 1474":"enne 1399–enne 1474","1399–1474":"1399–1474","–1422":"–1422","1380–1441":"1380–1441","1421–1507":"1421–1507","1350–1425":"1350–1425","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","about 1381":"umbes 1381","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","13 June 1441":"13. juuni 1441","1425":"1425","Bef 1399":"enne 1399